SWYFTDESKTOP ROADMAP
====================

PROJECT OVERVIEW
SwyftDesktop is a distributed computing system consisting of a mobile control layer and a lightweight desktop environment. The system enables a phone to act as a controller and runtime bridge for a custom desktop UI that can operate on low-spec devices while preserving phone usability.

Core principles:
- Phone remains fully usable during operation
- Desktop environment runs as a lightweight rendered shell
- UI and input are separated from execution logic
- Cross-device communication enables real-time interaction
- System is modular, themeable, and platform-adaptive

------------------------------------------------------------

PHASE 1 — MOBILE CORE LAUNCHER
Goal: Stable Android control hub and app interface layer

Features:
- Grid-based app drawer system
- Reliable app discovery via PackageManager
- AppTile UI component system
- Stable app launching via action dispatcher
- Fixes for package visibility limitations
- Basic sorting and layout management

Outcome:
Functional mobile control hub for system interaction

------------------------------------------------------------

PHASE 2 — MOBILE UI SYSTEM + WIDGET ENGINE
Goal: Build modular mobile interface system

Features:
- Home screen panel system
- Widget framework:
  - Clock widget
  - Shortcuts widget
  - System information widgets
- Reusable UI components:
  - AppTile
  - WidgetContainer
- Theme abstraction layer:
  - Material You (Android renderer)
  - Future Fluent mapping support
- Layout system separation from logic

Outcome:
Mobile UI becomes modular, extensible, and theme-driven

------------------------------------------------------------

PHASE 3 — ACTION + EVENT ARCHITECTURE
Goal: Centralise all system behaviour into a unified action model

Core system:
- Action dispatcher (single execution entry point)
- Event-driven UI architecture

Action types:
- LaunchApp
- OpenWidget
- OpenAppDrawer
- SystemCommand
- Future remote actions (PC bridge)

Outcome:
UI becomes declarative; logic is centralised and reusable

------------------------------------------------------------

PHASE 4 — INPUT SYSTEM (PHONE AS CONTROLLER)
Goal: Transform mobile device into input and control surface

Features:
- Touchpad mode for pointer control
- Gesture system:
  - Tap → left click
  - Long press → right click
  - Drag → scroll / move
- Keyboard input mode
- Real-time event streaming protocol

Output protocol:
- MOVE x y
- CLICK LEFT / RIGHT
- SCROLL delta
- KEY press/release

Outcome:
Phone functions as remote input device for desktop environment

------------------------------------------------------------

PHASE 5 — DESKTOP ENVIRONMENT (CORE SYSTEM)
Goal: Lightweight, custom desktop shell running on PC or tablet-class devices

This is the primary desktop experience layer, not an extension.

Features:
- Custom desktop UI shell (Swyft Desktop Environment)
- Window or panel-based layout system
- App rendering layer (apps appear as managed sessions)
- Custom taskbar system:
  - active apps
  - system controls
  - quick actions
- Widget support on desktop
- Dynamic layout engine (adapts to screen size and performance)
- Low overhead design for older hardware

UI design direction:
- Fluent UI-inspired design for Windows environments
- Clean, modular panels
- Adaptive density scaling for low-end devices

Outcome:
Fully custom desktop environment independent of OS shell

------------------------------------------------------------

PHASE 6 — DESKTOP CLIENT (RENDER + INPUT RECEIVER)
Goal: Desktop runtime that receives commands and renders environment

Features:
- Network input receiver (WebSocket or TCP)
- Session manager for apps and UI states
- Input injection layer (mouse + keyboard)
- Desktop UI renderer (Swyft shell)
- Performance scaling system for weak hardware

Outcome:
Desktop becomes a controllable, lightweight execution surface

------------------------------------------------------------

PHASE 7 — CROSS-DEVICE BRIDGE SYSTEM
Goal: Unified communication between phone and desktop

Features:
- Secure connection pairing system
- Real-time command streaming
- Device discovery
- Session persistence
- Multi-device support (future)

Outcome:
Phone and desktop operate as one system

------------------------------------------------------------

PHASE 8 — THEMING SYSTEM
Goal: Unified visual identity across all devices

System design:
- Abstract theme model shared across platforms
- Platform-specific renderers:
  - Android → Material You
  - Desktop → Fluent UI style system

Theme properties:
- spacing scale
- corner radius
- color system
- surface/material model
- motion rules

Outcome:
Consistent design language across all environments

------------------------------------------------------------

ARCHITECTURE PRINCIPLES
- Mobile and desktop are equal parts of the system
- UI is declarative; logic is centralised via actions
- Desktop environment is lightweight and adaptive
- All communication is event-based
- Platform-specific rendering is isolated at the edge
- System prioritises performance on low-spec hardware
